query: Answer the question in this video.
question_text:
A bead slides downward along a cycloidal track. Let a be the magnitude of its acceleration at some arbitrary point. Which relationship is correct?
(Hint: because the radius of curvature is small, a centripetal‐acceleration term is added.)
(A) a = g \sin\theta
(B) a > g \sin\theta
(C) a < g \sin\theta
(D) a = g (constant)
prediction:
(B) a > g sin θ  

Along the cycloid the bead’s tangential acceleration is g sin θ, but there is also a normal (centripetal) component v²/R directed toward the center of curvature.  
The magnitude of the total acceleration is  

a = √[(g sin θ)² + (v²/R)²] ,

which is necessarily larger than g sin θ, so a > g sin θ.

query: Answer the question in this video.
question_text:
Near the end of the video, when the number of slits is abruptly reduced to just two, the screen pattern becomes sparse with wide spacing. What does this best illustrate?
(A) Fewer slits make the principal maxima narrower."
(B) Fewer slits reduce the beam’s overall spread."
(C) Fewer slits increase fringe spacing and remove secondary minima."
(D) The number of slits has no effect on pattern position.
prediction:
Correct choice:  

(C) Fewer slits increase fringe spacing and remove secondary minima.

Explanation  
For a grating the principal-maxima angles (d sin θ = mλ) depend only on the slit spacing d, not on how many slits N are open.  
However, as N rises the factor (sin Nβ / sin β)² introduces (N–2) secondary maxima between any two principal maxima, making the pattern dense. When N is suddenly cut to 2, those intermediate (secondary) peaks disappear, so the remaining bright fringes are farther apart and the pattern looks “sparse with wide spacing.” The principal-maxima width actually broadens (not narrows) when N is reduced, ruling out the other options.

query: Answer the question in this video.
question_text:
A bead released from height h travels down a cycloidal path. At the point where its speed is v, the angle is \theta. For a bead that reaches the same speed v on a straight ramp, the angle is \theta{\prime}. Which statement is correct?
(A) \theta{\prime} < \theta
(B) \theta{\prime} = \theta
(C) \theta{\prime} > \theta
(D) The angles are independent of path shape
prediction:
For the same change in height the bead on the cycloid moves **less** horizontal distance than the bead on a straight incline.  
Indeed, when the beads have the same speed  

  Δy = v²/(2 g)                                              (identical vertical drop)

the straight ramp has carried the bead a horizontal distance  

  Δx ′ = Δy / tan θ′ .

Because the cycloid is the brachistochrone, it reaches that same vertical drop in the **shortest possible time**, which is only possible if it also covers the **shortest horizontal distance**:  

  Δx < Δx ′ .

Hence  

  tan θ = Δy / Δx  >  Δy / Δx ′ = tan θ′ ,

so

  θ > θ′ .

Therefore the angle of the cycloid is always steeper than that of the straight ramp at the moment the two beads have the same speed.

Correct choice: (A)  θ′ < θ

 T_cyc = π√(R/g) (or the same √g–dependence for any segment), so T_cyc ∝ 1/√g.

Hence both times double.

Answer: (A) T_line doubles, T_cyc doubles.

At the midpoint of each track (arc length = L/2), which track has the smallest kinetic energy (KE)?
(A) Straight
(B) Parabola
(C) Cycloid
(D) All the same
prediction:
The kinetic-energy a bead has at any point on a friction-free track is determined only by how far it has fallen ( Δy ) from the starting height, because  
m g Δy = K.E.  

• For the cycloid the bead plunges the fastest, so after half its arclength it has fallen the most and therefore has the largest K.E.  
• The straight track is in between.  
• The parabola starts off almost horizontally, so after travelling half its own length it is still the highest of the three and has converted the least potential energy into kinetic energy.

Hence the smallest kinetic energy at the midpoint (L⁄2) is on the

(B) Parabola.
